              <h2>How this Texas sales tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool helps you estimate Texas sales and use tax for
                everyday transactions. It supports three modes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>From price:</strong> Enter the price before tax and a
                  tax rate to get the tax amount and total.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>From total:</strong> Enter the total (price + tax) to
                  reverse-calculate the pre-tax price and tax portion.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tax only:</strong> Quickly compute just the tax amount
                  from a price.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Formulas used</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>1. Tax from price (before tax)</strong></p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li><code>P</code> = price before tax</li>
                  <li>
                    <code>r</code> = tax rate as a decimal (e.g., 8.25% →
                    0.0825)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then:</p>
                <pre>
Tax = P × r
Total = P × (1 + r)</pre
                >

                <p class="mt-3">
                  <strong>2. Reverse: tax from total (price + tax)</strong>
                </p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li><code>T</code> = total price (with tax)</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then:</p>
                <pre>
Price before tax = T ÷ (1 + r)
Tax = T − Price before tax</pre
                >
              </div>

              <h2>Texas state and local sales tax basics</h2>
              <p>
                Texas imposes a
                <strong>state sales and use tax of 6.25%</strong> on most
                taxable goods and some services. Local jurisdictions (cities,
                counties, transit authorities, and special purpose districts)
                can add their own sales and use taxes.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>State rate:</strong> 6.25%</li>
                <li><strong>Maximum local rate:</strong> 2.00%</li>
                <li><strong>Maximum combined rate:</strong> 8.25%</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Actual local rates vary by location. This calculator lets you
                plug in the exact combined rate you need (for example, 8.25% for
                many large cities, or a lower rate for rural areas).
              </p>

              <h3>What is taxable in Texas?</h3>
              <p>In general, Texas sales tax applies to:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Most tangible personal property (retail goods, electronics,
                  furniture, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Many taxable services (telecommunications, some labor,
                  amusements, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>Prepared food and restaurant meals.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Common exemptions include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Most groceries and unprepared food.</li>
                <li>Prescription medicines and some medical devices.</li>
                <li>Certain manufacturing and agricultural items.</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                Always confirm taxability and current rates with the
                <a
                  href="https://comptroller.texas.gov/taxes/sales/"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  >Texas Comptroller of Public Accounts</a
                >
                or a qualified tax professional.
              </p>

              <h2>Examples</h2>
              <h3>Example 1 – $100 purchase at 8.25%</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Price before tax: $100.00</li>
                <li>Rate: 8.25% (0.0825)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Tax = 100 × 0.0825 = <strong>$8.25</strong><br />
                Total = 100 × 1.0825 = <strong>$108.25</strong>
              </p>

              <h3>Example 2 – Reverse-calculate from total</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Total paid: $216.50</li>
                <li>Rate: 8.25% (0.0825)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Price before tax = 216.50 ÷ 1.0825 ≈ <strong>$200.00</strong
                ><br />
                Tax = 216.50 − 200.00 = <strong>$16.50</strong>
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and disclaimer</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is for
                <strong>educational and planning purposes only</strong>. It does
                not file returns, determine nexus, or replace professional
                advice. Texas sales and use tax rules are complex and change
                over time.
              </p>
              <p>
                For official guidance, current rates, and filing requirements,
                consult the
                <a
                  href="https://comptroller.texas.gov/taxes/sales/"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  >Texas Comptroller</a
                >
                or a licensed tax professional.
              </p>
